    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Reliability, Limitations, and AI-Generated Content Affecting Daily Posts Metrics\n\nBased on the provided S-1 preamble chunks, the most direct and relevant language regarding the interpretability of the "daily posts" metric—and how AI-generated content affects it—appears in the **definitions section**:\n\n> **"daily posts" on X and Grok refers to the aggregate volume of original posts, replies, reposts, quotes and media shared daily by users on the X platform, and the real-time interactions, analysis and generative capabilities provided to a user by Grok. This may include posts generated by AI or accounts managed by AI.**\n\nThis definition is significant for several reasons:\n\n1. **Explicit acknowledgment of AI-generated content inflating the metric**: The phrase *"This may include posts generated by AI or accounts managed by AI"* is a direct interpretability caveat. It signals that the daily posts figure is not a pure measure of human user activity and could be materially affected by automated or AI-driven content generation.\n\n2. **Conflation of human and AI activity**: The metric aggregates both human user posts *and* Grok\'s real-time interactions, analysis, and generative capabilities into a single volume figure, making it difficult to distinguish organic human engagement from AI-assisted or AI-generated output.\n\n3. **Use as a competitive differentiator**: Later in the preamble, the company cites this metric as evidence of Grok\'s strength:\n\n> **"With approximately 350 million daily posts, X enables freshness, relevance, and contextual awareness for Grok that we believe is a competitive differentiator."**\n\nThis means the same metric that is acknowledged to potentially include AI-generated content is also being used to substantiate the platform\'s competitive positioning—creating a tension between the metric\'s marketing utility and its reliability as a measure of genuine human discourse.\n\n---\n\n## Absence of MAU-Specific Caveats\n\nNotably, **none of the provided chunks contain a definition of "Monthly Active Users" (MAU)** or any explicit risk factor discussing how AI-generated content affects MAU reliability. The provided text only addresses the "daily posts" metric in this regard.\n\n---\n\n## Related Risk Context\n\nWhile not framed specifically as a metric-reliability risk, the broader risk factor language about AI outputs being flawed or misused provides indirect context for why AI-influenced metrics could be unreliable:\n\n> **"AI technologies, the models, algorithms, prompts and datasets on which they rely, and the recommendations, forecasts, analyses or other output that such AI technologies assist in producing, may be flawed, insufficient, of poor quality, rely upon incorrect, inaccurate, harmful or illegal data, reflect unwanted forms of bias, hallucinate, misrepresent, mislead or contain other errors or inadequacies, any of which may not be easily detectable."**\n\n> **"certain of our AI products, such as Grok, have been alleged to be susceptible to \'data poisoning\' in the past."**\n\nThese statements, while focused on output quality rather than metric integrity, underscore that AI-generated content contributing to the daily posts volume may itself be unreliable or manipulated—further complicating the interpretability of the aggregate metric.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nThe S-1 preamble provides **one explicit note** on how AI-generated content affects the daily posts metric (the definition stating it "may include posts generated by AI or accounts managed by AI"), but offers **no parallel caveat for MAU** and does not include a dedicated risk factor specifically addressing the distortion of engagement metrics by AI-generated content. The closest supporting context comes from general AI output-quality risk disclosures.',
